				 Italian FDI yet to gather pace
 A STAFF REPORTER				 	 Bruno Campria (right) with BNCCI president K.K. Navada in Calcutta on Tuesday. A Telegraph picture																								Calcutta, Nov. 27: India, including Bengal, has a long way to go in attracting investments from Italy, which dropped to 69.6 million euros in 2006-07 from 2.17 billion euros in 2005-06.																								Lack of bilateral contacts plagues the investment scenario. Though it will take time but the progress of MoUs signed in February is especially slow in Bengal compared to New Delhi and Mumbai, said Bruno Campria, consul-general of Italy in Calcutta.																								Campria was speaking at an interactive session organised by the Bengal National Chamber of Commerce and Industry. During the first half of this year, Italian FDI was down to 23.2 million euros against 55.1 million euros in the corresponding period of the previous year.																								Its high time that trading partners became investment partners as well. The special economic zone model will also be key to attracting more Italian companies to set up shop in the state, said Campria. 
